Note:
==============================================================================
ARGON2ID - Memory-hard password hashing per RFC 9106
==============================================================================

Argon2id is the hybrid variant of the Argon2 family (Argon2d / Argon2i /
Argon2id) winning the Password Hashing Competition (2015). It is the
RFC-recommended variant for password hashing, KDF and proof-of-work because
it provides:

  - Memory-hardness: large working set (m KB of 1024-byte blocks) forces
    attackers using ASIC/FPGA/GPU to spend ~m * t memory-time product on
    each guess; cannot be parallelized below this floor by time-memory
    tradeoff (TMTO) attacks that reduce memory cost at the expense of
    additional computation -- Argon2d's data-dependent addressing in
    passes 1+ forces the attacker to materialize the full matrix.

  - Side-channel resistance for the first half pass: Argon2i (data-INdependent
    indexing) on segments 0 and 1 of pass 0 means the password-derived
    early blocks are accessed at indices that do not depend on the password
    contents. This defeats cache-timing side-channel attacks that would
    otherwise be feasible against pure-Argon2d.

  - The hybrid construction (Argon2i for the first half pass, Argon2d for
    the rest) thus simultaneously resists TMTO (Argon2d's contribution)
    and cache-timing side-channels on the password-knowing early blocks
    (Argon2i's contribution).

Algorithm structure (RFC 9106):

  1. Pre-hashing H_0 = BLAKE2b(
       LE32(p) || LE32(T) || LE32(m) || LE32(t) || LE32(v=0x13) || LE32(y=2)
       || LE32(|P|) || P || LE32(|S|) || S || LE32(|K|) || K
       || LE32(|X|) || X
     ), 64 bytes.

     where p=parallelism, T=tag length, m=memory cost, t=iterations,
     v=0x13 (version 1.3), y=2 (Argon2id type), P=password, S=salt,
     K=secret key (may be empty), X=associated data (may be empty).

  2. Memory matrix B[p][q] of 1024-byte blocks, q = m_prime / p, where
     m_prime = floor(m / (4p)) * 4p. Segment length SL = q / 4.

  3. Initial blocks per lane i = 0 .. p-1:
       B[i][0] = H'( H_0 || LE32(0) || LE32(i), 1024 bytes )
       B[i][1] = H'( H_0 || LE32(1) || LE32(i), 1024 bytes )

  4. For pass r = 0 .. t-1:
       For slice s = 0 .. 3:                  Note: slice = segment column
         For each lane i = 0 .. p-1 in parallel:
           For position j in segment (r=0, s=0: j starts at 2; else j=0):
             Compute next block B[i][s*SL + j] = G( prev_block, ref_block )
             where the previous block is the last block computed in this
             lane, and the reference block is chosen by the indexing rule:
               - Argon2id, r=0, s in {0,1}: data-independent (Argon2i)
                 indexing: J1, J2 from the addressing-block pseudorandom
                 stream produced by applying G to a counter block.
               - All other (r, s): data-dependent (Argon2d) indexing:
                 J1, J2 are the first two uint32 words of prev_block.

  5. Final block C = XOR of B[i][q-1] for all lanes i.

  6. Tag = H'(C, T bytes) into caller-supplied output buffer.

Internal primitives implemented inline in this file:

  - BLAKE2b: full-output (up to 64 bytes) Blake2b hash per RFC 7693.
  - H' (RFC 9106 section 3.3): variable-length hash chaining Blake2b to
    produce arbitrary-length outputs (used to produce 1024-byte blocks
    and the final T-byte tag).
  - G (RFC 9106 section 3.5): the Argon2 compression function. Takes
    two 1024-byte blocks X, Y; produces a 1024-byte block Z. Built from
    the Blake2b round function P applied to 8 rows then 8 columns of
    R = X XOR Y, with a final XOR of R back into the permuted matrix.

Numerical conventions:
  - All integer values are stored little-endian per RFC 9106 section 3.
  - LE32 / LE64 helpers serialise uint32 / uint64 values to memory.
  - 64-bit modular arithmetic is performed using the 64-bit mask U64_MASK.

Parameter validation (returns 0 on failure):
  - m < 8*p  (RFC 9106 section 3.1 minimum memory: m must be at least 8*p
              so segment_length = floor(m / (4p)) / 4 >= 2).
  - t < 1, p < 1.
  - output_len < 4, output_len > 0xFFFFFFFF.
  - salt_len < 8 (RFC 9106 minimum salt length).
  - All buffer pointers null with positive length.

Memory and timing posture:
  - Memory: the m KB matrix is the dominant allocation. For the RFC 9106
    Appendix B vector (m=32, p=4) this is 32 KB plus working blocks.
  - Argon2i addressing produces 128 (J1, J2) pairs per address block; we
    regenerate the address block at slice boundaries by zero-init then
    applying G(zero, X) twice with X = (r, lane, slice, total_blocks,
    iterations, type=2, counter, zero_pad). RFC 9106 section 3.4 part 1.b.

References:
  - RFC 9106, "Argon2 Memory-Hard Function for Password Hashing and
    Proof-of-Work Applications", A. Biryukov, D. Dinu, D. Khovratovich,
    S. Josefsson.
  - RFC 7693, "The BLAKE2 Cryptographic Hash and Message Authentication
    Code (MAC)", M-J. Saarinen, J-P. Aumasson.
  - Biryukov, Dinu, Khovratovich, "Argon2: the memory-hard function for
    password hashing and other applications", 2017 PHC submission.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "runtime/core/memory/arena.runa" as Arena
Import "compiler/frontend/import_system/crypto/secure_memory.runa" as SecureMem

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Section 0: Constants
Note: ============================================================================

Constant ARGON2_BLOCK_SIZE as Integer is 1024
Constant ARGON2_QWORDS_PER_BLOCK as Integer is 128
Constant ARGON2_VERSION_13 as Integer is 19
Constant ARGON2_TYPE_ID as Integer is 2
Constant ARGON2_SYNC_POINTS as Integer is 4
Constant ARGON2_PREHASH_DIGEST_LEN as Integer is 64
Constant ARGON2_PREHASH_SEED_LEN as Integer is 72
Constant BLAKE2B_OUT_BYTES as Integer is 64
Constant BLAKE2B_BLOCK_BYTES as Integer is 128
Constant U64_MASK as Integer is 18446744073709551615
Constant U32_MASK_A2 as Integer is 4294967295
Constant U8_MASK as Integer is 255

Note: BLAKE2b IV (RFC 7693 section 2.6) -- fractional bits of sqrt of first 8 primes.
Constant BLAKE2B_IV0 as Integer is 7640891576956012808
Constant BLAKE2B_IV1 as Integer is 13503953896175478587
Constant BLAKE2B_IV2 as Integer is 4354685564936845355
Constant BLAKE2B_IV3 as Integer is 11912009170470909681
Constant BLAKE2B_IV4 as Integer is 5840696475078001361
Constant BLAKE2B_IV5 as Integer is 11170449401992604703
Constant BLAKE2B_IV6 as Integer is 2270897969802886507
Constant BLAKE2B_IV7 as Integer is 6620516959819538809

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Section 1: 64-bit arithmetic helpers
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "argon2_u64_add" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Modular 64-bit addition: (a + b) mod 2^64. Runa Integer is 64-bit
    signed so plain addition wraps in two's complement, which is the
    correct uint64 modular result after masking.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Plain addition followed by bitwise_and with U64_MASK. Both inputs
    must already be in [0, 2^64). The mask is a no-op on the value bits
    but ensures the result reads back as a positive Integer when used
    as a uint64.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single add plus one mask. Sub-nanosecond. RFC 9106 reference impl
    achieves the same in two instructions on x86-64.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time: timing independent of operand values.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let sum_value be a plus b
    Return sum_value bitwise_and U64_MASK
End Process

Process called "argon2_u64_mul_low" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Computes the low 64 bits of a * b. Used in the BLAKE2b round function
    P's modified addition step where Argon2 specifies
    2 * (a_low32 * b_low32) addition rather than the original BLAKE2b
    plain addition.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Multiplies a by b modulo 2^64. Runa Integer is 64-bit signed so the
    result naturally truncates to the low 64 bits in two's-complement,
    after which masking with U64_MASK normalises to unsigned.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Single multiply plus mask. On x86-64 this is a single IMUL.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time on every CPU we target. IMUL latency is fixed.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let product be a multiplied by b
    Return product bitwise_and U64_MASK
End Process

Process called "argon2_low32" takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the low 32 bits of value as a uint32 (0..2^32-1).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Single AND with U32_MASK_A2 = 2^32 - 1.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints Sub-nanosecond. @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope Constant-time. @End Security_Scope

    Return value bitwise_and U32_MASK_A2
End Process

Process called "argon2_rotr64" takes value as Integer, n as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Rotate-right of a uint64 by n bits (0 <= n < 64). Used in the
    BLAKE2b round function P with rotation constants 32, 24, 16, 63.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Splits value into the low n bits and the high (64-n) bits, then
    re-assembles with the low bits moved to the top. Implemented with
    a power-of-two divide for the right shift (preserving sign-free
    behaviour via the U64 mask) and a power-of-two multiply for the
    left shift, OR-combined and masked to 64 bits.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Three integer ops plus two power-of-two loops to construct the
    shift constants. A future Runa codegen pass can lower this to a
    single ROR instruction on x86-64.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time: timing depends only on n (loop-invariant in Blake2b
    where the rotation constants are fixed).
    @End Security_Scope

    Let n_mod be n modulo by 64
    If n_mod is equal to 0:
        Return value bitwise_and U64_MASK
    End If

    Let shift_left be 1
    Let il be 0
    Let left_count be 64 minus n_mod
    While il is less than left_count:
        Set shift_left to shift_left multiplied by 2
        Set il to il plus 1
    End While

    Let shift_right be 1
    Let ir be 0
    While ir is less than n_mod:
        Set shift_right to shift_right multiplied by 2
        Set ir to ir plus 1
    End While

    Let v_masked be value bitwise_and U64_MASK
    Let left_part be v_masked multiplied by shift_left
    Set left_part to left_part bitwise_and U64_MASK
    Let right_part be v_masked divided by shift_right
    Let combined be left_part bitwise_or right_part
    Return combined bitwise_and U64_MASK
End Process

Process called "argon2_load64_le" takes ptr as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Loads 8 bytes from ptr[offset..offset+8] as a little-endian uint64.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Reads 8 individual bytes and reassembles via shifts and OR. The
    cost is fixed and constant-time; on a future codegen pass with
    unaligned 64-bit loads enabled this can lower to a single MOV.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Eight byte loads plus seven shifts plus seven ORs. Future SIMD
    codegen can fuse to a single 64-bit unaligned load.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time. No secret-dependent indexing into ptr beyond offset
    which is loop-counter driven, not data-driven.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let b0 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with ptr, offset
    Let b1 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with ptr, offset plus 1
    Let b2 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with ptr, offset plus 2
    Let b3 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with ptr, offset plus 3
    Let b4 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with ptr, offset plus 4
    Let b5 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with ptr, offset plus 5
    Let b6 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with ptr, offset plus 6
    Let b7 be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with ptr, offset plus 7

    Let r be b0
    Set r to r bitwise_or (b1 multiplied by 256)
    Set r to r bitwise_or (b2 multiplied by 65536)
    Set r to r bitwise_or (b3 multiplied by 16777216)
    Set r to r bitwise_or (b4 multiplied by 4294967296)
    Set r to r bitwise_or (b5 multiplied by 1099511627776)
    Set r to r bitwise_or (b6 multiplied by 281474976710656)
    Set r to r bitwise_or (b7 multiplied by 72057594037927936)
    Return r bitwise_and U64_MASK
End Process

Process called "argon2_store64_le" takes ptr as Integer, offset as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Stores a uint64 to ptr[offset..offset+8] in little-endian order.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Extracts each of the 8 bytes via a divide-by-power-of-2 then AND
    with 0xFF and writes them to consecutive byte positions.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Eight stores. Future codegen can lower to a single 64-bit unaligned
    write.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let v be value bitwise_and U64_MASK
    Let b0 be v bitwise_and U8_MASK
    Let b1 be (v divided by 256) bitwise_and U8_MASK
    Let b2 be (v divided by 65536) bitwise_and U8_MASK
    Let b3 be (v divided by 16777216) bitwise_and U8_MASK
    Let b4 be (v divided by 4294967296) bitwise_and U8_MASK
    Let b5 be (v divided by 1099511627776) bitwise_and U8_MASK
    Let b6 be (v divided by 281474976710656) bitwise_and U8_MASK
    Let b7 be (v divided by 72057594037927936) bitwise_and U8_MASK
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with ptr, offset, b0
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with ptr, offset plus 1, b1
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with ptr, offset plus 2, b2
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with ptr, offset plus 3, b3
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with ptr, offset plus 4, b4
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with ptr, offset plus 5, b5
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with ptr, offset plus 6, b6
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with ptr, offset plus 7, b7
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "argon2_store32_le" takes ptr as Integer, offset as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Stores a uint32 to ptr[offset..offset+4] in little-endian order.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Four byte stores via AND-and-divide.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints Sub-nanosecond. @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope Constant-time. @End Security_Scope

    Let v be value bitwise_and U32_MASK_A2
    Let b0 be v bitwise_and U8_MASK
    Let b1 be (v divided by 256) bitwise_and U8_MASK
    Let b2 be (v divided by 65536) bitwise_and U8_MASK
    Let b3 be (v divided by 16777216) bitwise_and U8_MASK
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with ptr, offset, b0
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with ptr, offset plus 1, b1
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with ptr, offset plus 2, b2
    proc memory_set_byte from Memory with ptr, offset plus 3, b3
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Section 2: BLAKE2b core
Note: ============================================================================
Note: BLAKE2b RFC 7693 -- variable-output cryptographic hash; the
Note: building-block we need for H_0 (the pre-hash) and H' (the variable-
Note: length hash used to produce 1024-byte blocks and the final tag).
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "blake2b_g_mix" takes v as Integer, ia as Integer, ib as Integer, ic as Integer, id as Integer, x as Integer, y as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    BLAKE2b G mixing function operating on four uint64 state words v[ia],
    v[ib], v[ic], v[id] with two uint64 message words x and y. This is
    the BLAKE2b round-function step (RFC 7693 section 3.1), NOT the
    Argon2 compression function G (those share a name in spec).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Per RFC 7693 section 3.1:
      a = a + b + x
      d = (d XOR a) >>> 32
      c = c + d
      b = (b XOR c) >>> 24
      a = a + b + y
      d = (d XOR a) >>> 16
      c = c + d
      b = (b XOR c) >>> 63
    All additions are modulo 2^64. The state v is a 16-uint64 array
    stored at v[0..127] (8 bytes per slot).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Eight 64-bit adds, four XORs, four rotates. The hot loop of
    Blake2b is 12 rounds, each invoking G eight times, so ~96 G calls
    per 128-byte compression. Future SIMD codegen can pack columns
    into AVX2 registers.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time. No secret-dependent branches or memory accesses.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let off_a be ia multiplied by 8
    Let off_b be ib multiplied by 8
    Let off_c be ic multiplied by 8
    Let off_d be id multiplied by 8

    Let va be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with v, off_a
    Let vb be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with v, off_b
    Let vc be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with v, off_c
    Let vd be proc memory_get_qword from Memory with v, off_d

    Let sum_ab be proc argon2_u64_add with va, vb
    Set va to proc argon2_u64_add with sum_ab, x
    Let xor_da be vd bitwise_xor va
    Set vd to proc argon2_rotr64 with xor_da, 32

    Set vc to proc argon2_u64_add with vc, vd
    Let xor_bc be vb bitwise_xor vc
    Set vb to proc argon2_rotr64 with xor_bc, 24

    Let sum_ab2 be proc argon2_u64_add with va, vb
    Set va to proc argon2_u64_add with sum_ab2, y
    Let xor_da2 be vd bitwise_xor va
    Set vd to proc argon2_rotr64 with xor_da2, 16

    Set vc to proc argon2_u64_add with vc, vd
    Let xor_bc2 be vb bitwise_xor vc
    Set vb to proc argon2_rotr64 with xor_bc2, 63

    proc memory_set_qword from Memory with v, off_a, va
    proc memory_set_qword from Memory with v, off_b, vb
    proc memory_set_qword from Memory with v, off_c, vc
    proc memory_set_qword from Memory with v, off_d, vd
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "blake2b_sigma" takes round_idx as Integer, pos as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the SIGMA[round_idx mod 10][pos] permutation entry for the
    BLAKE2b message schedule. SIGMA is 10 rows of 16 entries each
    (RFC 7693 section 2.7); round 10 and 11 of BLAKE2b reuse rows 0
    and 1 (round_idx mod 10).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Encoded as a flat 160-entry table built into a Match expression
    keyed on (round_idx mod 10) * 16 + pos. Each entry is in 0..15.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Table lookup. The compiler will lower a sequence of When clauses
    into a jump table.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time at the algorithmic level: round_idx and pos are
    loop counters, not secret-dependent.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let r be round_idx modulo by 10
    Let idx be (r multiplied by 16) plus pos
    Match idx:
        When 0:
            Return 0
        When 1:
            Return 1
        When 2:
            Return 2
        When 3:
            Return 3
        When 4:
            Return 4
        When 5:
            Return 5
        When 6:
            Return 6
        When 7:
            Return 7
        When 8:
            Return 8
        When 9:
            Return 9
        When 10:
            Return 10
        When 11:
            Return 11
        When 12:
            Return 12
        When 13:
            Return 13
        When 14:
            Return 14
        When 15:
            Return 15
        When 16:
            Return 14
        When 17:
            Return 10
        When 18:
            Return 4
        When 19:
